📌 JavaScript Error Handling


🔹 What Errors Are in JavaScript

Errors are problems that occur while your code is running, such as:
Syntax errors → invalid code (caught at compile time)
Runtime errors → code runs but fails
Logical errors → code runs but produces wrong results

🔹 Why Error Handling Matters
Prevents app crashes
Provides graceful failure
Helps debug and log useful info
Improves user experience


🔹 Using try and catch Blocks
try → contains code that may throw an error
catch → handles the error

try {
    let result = riskyFunction();
    console.log(result);
} catch (error) {
    console.log("Caught an error:", error.message);
}

execution flow
try {
    // code that might fail
} catch (error) {
    // runs if an error occurs
}

If no error → catch skipped
If error → jumps to catch


🔹 The finally Block
Runs always, regardless of error
Useful for cleanup tasks


try {
    console.log("Try block running");
    // throw new Error("Oops!");
} catch (error) {
    console.log("Caught error:", error.message);
} finally {
    console.log("Finally block runs always");
}

//output with error
Try block running
Caught error: Oops!
Finally block runs always

Why is finally used, if try catch are already there?
🔹 What finally Does
The finally block always runs, no matter what happens in try or catch.
It is guaranteed to execute even if:
An error occurs
There’s a return statement inside try or catch
An error is thrown and caught

🔹 Why Not Just try…catch?

try…catch only handles errors.

Code in try runs → success or error
If error → catch runs
But cleanup or finishing tasks may need to happen regardless of success or failure

Example - Closing resource
function readFile() {
    let file = openFile("data.txt"); // hypothetical
    try {
        console.log(file.readData());
    } catch (err) {
        console.log("Error reading file:", err.message);
    } finally {
        file.close(); // must run no matter what
    }
}

If reading succeeds → finally still closes the file
If reading fails → catch handles the error, then finally closes the file

Without finally, you might forget to close resources, causing leaks or inconsistent state.

finally is for cleanup / guaranteed execution

🔹 Throwing Custom Errors

function checkAge(age) {
    if (age < 18) {
        throw new Error("Age must be at least 18");
    }
    return "Access granted";
}

try {
    console.log(checkAge(15));
} catch (err) {
    console.log("Error:", err.message);
}
//output
Error: Age must be at least 18



⚠️ Why Use Custom Errors
Makes debugging easier
Provides meaningful messages
Improves code readability and maintenance

No error path:
try runs → no error
finally runs
Continue after try…finally


Error occurs path:
try runs → error
catch runs → handles error
finally runs → always executes
Continue after try…catch…finally
